# Professional Documentation Standards for OSS Projects

This ruleset establishes comprehensive documentation practices for GitHub open-source projects, ensuring clear communication across developers, collaborators, and users. Based on the Diátaxis framework and industry best practices, this guideline balances clarity, conciseness, and structure.

---

## Core Documentation Principles

### Keep It Clear

- Use plain language accessible to your target audience
- Define or replace acronyms and technical terms that may not be universally understood
- Avoid jargon unless necessary; if used, define it clearly
- Write for humans first—consider if documentation helps readers understand and maintain the code
- Use active voice and direct language
- Break complex concepts into digestible sections
- Provide context before introducing technical details

### Keep It Concise

- Document only necessary information relevant to the majority of users
- Avoid exhaustive coverage of edge cases; link to separate documents instead
- Focus each document on a single topic or task
- Remove redundant information and consolidate related content
- Use lists, tables, and formatting to reduce word count
- Keep paragraphs short (3-5 sentences maximum)
- Cut out filler words and unnecessary elaboration

### Keep It Structured

- Place the most important information first (inverted pyramid)
- Use clear headings and table of contents for easy scanning
- Employ consistent text highlighting (bold for key terms, italics for emphasis)
- Limit emphasis to approximately 10% of text to maintain impact
- Maintain consistent styling across all documents
- Use formatting elements (lists, code blocks, tables) strategically
- Ensure logical flow and clear hierarchy

